================================================================================
ABSTRACT — RELATIONAL COSMOLOGICAL GEOMETRY (RCG)
================================================================================

We introduce Relational Cosmological Geometry (RCG), a framework in which the
large‑scale structure of the cosmic microwave background (CMB) arises from a
relational density field and its induced boundary geometry. RCG replaces the
assumption of primordial Gaussian metric fluctuations with a geometry generated
by the operator 𝓖 = −∇² + μΔρ + ν û·∇ acting on relational densities ρ₊ and ρ₋.

The lowest nontrivial eigenmode of 𝓖, projected onto the last‑scattering
surface, yields a global boundary deformation M_{2,3}(n̂) that reproduces the
observed quadrupole–octopole alignment and defines a preferred cosmic axis.
A screening length d_s = d₀ exp[−α Δρ/τ] produces a finite‑range angular
coupling kernel K(θ), naturally generating the observed suppression of
large‑angle correlations.

The same parameters that fit the low‑ℓ temperature anomalies determine the
anisotropic lensing modulation amplitudes α₁ and α₂ through closure relations
β_Q = k_Q A_Q and β_D = k_D A_D. RCG therefore predicts correlated signatures
in lensing, polarization, and the ISW effect without introducing additional
degrees of freedom.

Localized ρ₋ defects generate Cold‑Spot‑like features with weak lensing and
subtle polarization structure, consistent with current observations. High‑ℓ
isotropy is preserved through spectral cutoff and short‑range coupling.

RCG provides a unified geometric origin for the CMB anomaly sector and yields
testable predictions for future CMB lensing and polarization surveys.

