INTRODUCTION — RELATIONAL COSMOLOGICAL GEOMETRY (RCG)
================================================================================

The standard ΛCDM model successfully describes the acoustic structure of the
cosmic microwave background (CMB) at high multipoles, yet exhibits persistent
tensions at large angular scales: the quadrupole–octopole alignment, the
hemispherical power asymmetry, the suppression of large‑angle correlations,
parity asymmetry, and the Cold Spot. These features violate statistical
isotropy and lack a natural origin within Gaussian primordial perturbations.

Relational Cosmological Geometry (RCG) addresses these anomalies by replacing
metric‑first cosmology with a geometry emerging from relational densities.
Two fields, ρ₊ and ρ₋, encode positive and negative tension contributions.
Their contrast Δρ and total τ determine both the geometry operator 𝓖 and the
screening length d_s that governs relational propagation.

The operator 𝓖 = −∇² + μΔρ + ν û·∇ possesses a lowest nontrivial eigenmode
whose boundary projection M_{2,3}(n̂) defines a global deformation of the
last‑scattering surface. This mode reproduces the observed quadrupole–octopole
alignment and establishes a preferred cosmic axis.

Finite‑range coupling arises from the screening length
d_s = d₀ exp[−α Δρ/τ], producing an angular kernel K(θ) with a natural cutoff
scale. This mechanism explains the lack of large‑angle correlation without
fine‑tuning.

Crucially, the amplitudes A_Q and A_D that fit the low‑ℓ temperature anomalies
also determine the anisotropic lensing modulation α₁ and α₂ through closure
relations β_Q = k_Q A_Q and β_D = k_D A_D. RCG therefore predicts correlated
signatures across temperature, lensing, polarization, and ISW observables.

Localized regions with Δρ < 0 act as tension defects, generating Cold‑Spot‑like
features with weak lensing and subtle polarization patterns, consistent with
Planck data.

RCG thus provides a unified geometric origin for the CMB anomaly sector and
offers falsifiable predictions for upcoming CMB lensing and polarization
surveys.

================================================================================
FORMAL DEFINITION — RELATIONAL COSMOLOGICAL GEOMETRY (RCG)
================================================================================

Relational Cosmological Geometry (RCG) is a cosmological framework in which
the large‑scale structure, anisotropy, and observable sky patterns arise from
a relational density field and its induced boundary geometry, rather than from
metric fluctuations of a primordial Gaussian random field.

RCG is defined by the following components:

1. Relational Density Fields:
      ρ₊(x)  = positive‑tension relational density
      ρ₋(x)  = negative‑tension relational density
      Δρ(x)  = ρ₊(x) − ρ₋(x)
      τ(x)   = ρ₊(x) + ρ₋(x)

2. Geometry Operator:
      𝓖Ψ(x) = −∇²Ψ(x) + μ Δρ(x) Ψ(x) + ν (û · ∇Ψ(x))

   where μ, ν are coupling constants and û is a global anisotropy direction.

3. Boundary Mode:
      𝓖Ψ₀ = λ₀ Ψ₀
      M_{2,3}(n̂) = Ψ₀(χ_*, n̂)

   The boundary eigenmode M_{2,3} encodes the aligned quadrupole–octopole
   structure and defines the global Q‑boundary mode.

4. Screening Length:
      d_s(x) = d₀ exp[ −α Δρ(x)/τ(x) ]

   which determines the finite‑range relational propagator.

5. Relational Propagator:
      G(d;x) = exp( − d / d_s(x) )

6. Angular Coupling Kernel:
      K(θ) = ∫ dχ W(χ) exp[ − d(χ,θ) / d_s(χ,n̂) ]

   which produces a finite correlation range on the sky.

7. Observable Fields:
      T(n̂) = T_iso + A_Q M_{2,3}(n̂) + A_D (d̂ · n̂)
      φ(n̂) = φ_iso + β_Q M_{2,3}(n̂) + β_D (d̂ · n̂)

   with closure relations β_Q = k_Q A_Q and β_D = k_D A_D.

RCG is the theory defined by the tuple:
      (ρ₊, ρ₋, 𝓖, d_s, G, K, M_{2,3})

from which all cosmological observables are derived.

================================================================================
1. CORE GEOMETRY OPERATOR 𝓖
================================================================================

Relational density fields:
    Δρ(x) = ρ₊(x) - ρ₋(x)        (signed imbalance)
    τ(x)  = ρ₊(x) + ρ₋(x)        (total tension)

Preferred direction (Axis of Evil):
    û = fixed unit vector

Minimal RDG geometry operator:
    𝓖 Ψ(x) =
        - ∇²Ψ(x)
        + μ Δρ(x) Ψ(x)
        + ν (û · ∇Ψ(x))

Interpretation:
    -∇²Ψ          → isotropic relational Laplacian  
    μ Δρ Ψ        → tension‑mass term from ρ₊/ρ₋  
    ν û·∇Ψ        → global anisotropic drift (Axis of Evil)

Lowest nontrivial eigenmode:
    𝓖 Ψ₀ = λ₀ Ψ₀

Boundary projection onto last‑scattering sphere:
    M_{2,3}(n̂) = Ψ₀(χ_*, n̂)

This M_{2,3}(n̂) is the aligned quadrupole–octopole pattern.

================================================================================
2. SCREENING LENGTH d_s(ρ₊,ρ₋) AND FINITE‑RANGE COUPLING
================================================================================

Define screening length:
    d_s(x) = d₀ * exp[ - α (Δρ(x) / τ(x)) ]

Meaning:
    Δρ > 0  → long‑range coupling  
    Δρ < 0  → short‑range coupling (Cold Spot region)

Relational propagator:
    G(d; x) = exp( - d / d_s(x) )

Angular coupling kernel on sky:
    K(θ) = ∫ dχ  W(χ)  exp( - d(χ,θ) / d_s(χ,n̂) )

This produces:
    • finite‑range coupling  
    • hard cutoff at θ ≳ θ_s  
    • explains lack of large‑angle correlation in CMB

================================================================================
3. LOW‑ℓ TEMPERATURE FIELD (FITTING STAGE)
================================================================================

Temperature field decomposition:
    T(n̂) = T_iso(n̂)
          + A_Q M_{2,3}(n̂)
          + A_D (d̂ · n̂)

Where:
    A_Q = amplitude of global Q‑boundary mode  
    A_D = amplitude of hemispherical asymmetry  
    d̂   = direction of power asymmetry

Fit A_Q, A_D, d̂ directly to observed a_{ℓm}^T for ℓ ≤ 30.

================================================================================
4. LENSING POTENTIAL φ(n̂) AND CLOSURE RELATIONS
================================================================================

Lensing potential:
    φ(n̂) = -2 ∫₀^{χ*} dχ [(χ* - χ)/(χ* χ)] Φ(χ n̂, η)

RDG anisotropic decomposition:
    φ(n̂) = φ_iso(n̂)
          + β_Q M_{2,3}(n̂)
          + β_D (d̂ · n̂)

Closure relations (no new parameters):
    β_Q = k_Q A_Q
    β_D = k_D A_D

Thus lensing anisotropy is fixed by the same A_Q, A_D that fit low‑ℓ T.

Directional lensing power:
    C_L^{φφ}(n̂) = C_L^{φφ,iso}
                   [1 + α₁ Y_{1m}(n̂) + α₂ Y_{2m}(n̂)]

Explicit proportionality:
    α₁ ∝ k_D A_D
    α₂ ∝ k_Q A_Q

================================================================================
5. EXPLICIT FORMULAS FOR α₁ AND α₂
================================================================================

Expand φ(n̂):
    φ(n̂) = Σ_{LM} a_{LM}^φ Y_{LM}(n̂)

Define anisotropic contributions:
    δa_{LM}^{φ,D} = β_D d_{LM}
    δa_{LM}^{φ,Q} = β_Q q_{LM}

Dipole modulation:
    α₁ =
      [ 2 Re( Σ_m a_{Lm}^{φ,iso*} δa_{Lm}^{φ,D} ) ]
      / [ Σ_m |a_{Lm}^{φ,iso}|² ]

Quadrupole modulation:
    α₂ =
      [ 2 Re( Σ_m a_{Lm}^{φ,iso*} δa_{Lm}^{φ,Q} ) ]
      / [ Σ_m |a_{Lm}^{φ,iso}|² ]

Insert closure:
    β_D = k_D A_D
    β_Q = k_Q A_Q

Final explicit forms:
    α₁ = (2 k_D A_D  Re Σ_m[a_{Lm}^{φ,iso*} d_{Lm}])
          / (Σ_m |a_{Lm}^{φ,iso}|²)

    α₂ = (2 k_Q A_Q  Re Σ_m[a_{Lm}^{φ,iso*} q_{Lm}])
          / (Σ_m |a_{Lm}^{φ,iso}|²)

================================================================================
6. ISW EFFECT (ANISOTROPIC CONTRIBUTIONS)
================================================================================

ISW temperature anisotropy:
    (ΔT/T)_ISW(n̂) = 2 ∫_{η*}^{η₀} dη  ∂Φ/∂η

Dipole ISW:
    (ΔT/T)_ISW^D(n̂) = γ_D (d̂ · n̂)

where:
    γ_D = 2 ∫ dη  [ dA_D/dη ] F_D(χ)

Quadrupole ISW:
    (ΔT/T)_ISW^Q(n̂) = γ_Q M_{2,3}(n̂)

where:
    γ_Q = 2 ∫ dη  [ dA_Q/dη ] F_Q(χ)

Thus:
    ISW anomalies ↔ same A_Q, A_D that set α₁, α₂.

================================================================================
7. COLD SPOT AS A ρ₋ DEFECT
================================================================================

Cold Spot region D:
    Δρ(D) << 0  → ρ₋‑dominated → short d_s → tension scar

Predictions:
    • temperature depression  
    • weak lensing convergence κ_D  
    • subtle E/B polarization modulation  
    • no strong mass signature (consistent with Planck lensing)

================================================================================
8. CONSISTENCY INEQUALITIES (PLANCK‑LEVEL)
================================================================================

Lensing isotropy:
    |α₁| ≤ 0.01
    |α₂| ≤ 0.01

High‑ℓ temperature isotropy:
    |ΔC_ℓ^{TT} / C_ℓ^{TT,iso}| ≤ ε_T   for ℓ > 100
    with ε_T ≪ 0.01

Cold Spot constraints:
    |κ_D| small
    |ΔEE| small
    |EB| small

Spectral cutoff:
    M_{2,3}(n̂) = 0 for ℓ > ℓ_c  (ℓ_c ≈ 30)

Finite‑range coupling:
    K(θ) ≈ 0 for θ ≳ θ_s

================================================================================
9. FULL RDG PIPELINE (END‑TO‑END)
================================================================================

Step 1 — Fit low‑ℓ temperature anomalies:
    Determine A_Q, A_D, d̂ from a_{ℓm}^T (ℓ ≤ 30)

Step 2 — Solve eigenproblem:
    𝓖Ψ₀ = λ₀Ψ₀ → obtain M_{2,3}(n̂)

Step 3 — Compute screening:
    d_s(ρ₊,ρ₋) → obtain K(θ)

Step 4 — Compute lensing anisotropy:
    β_Q = k_Q A_Q
    β_D = k_D A_D
    → α₁, α₂

Step 5 — Compute ISW anisotropy:
    γ_D, γ_Q

Step 6 — Enforce consistency inequalities:
    α₁, α₂, κ_D, ΔEE, EB, high‑ℓ isotropy

Step 7 — Compare with Planck TT, TE, EE, φφ, κ maps

